Instead Bran spent the morning alone in the godswood, trying to teach Bran wolf to fetch a stick, and failing. The wolfling was smarter than any of the hounds in The wolfling father's kennel and Bran would have sworn The wolfling understood every word that was said to The wolfling, but The wolfling showed very little interest in chasing sticks.  The wolfling was still trying to decide on a name. Robb was calling Robb Grey Wind, because Robb ran so fast. Sansa had named hers Lady, and Arya named hers after some old witch queen in the songs, and little Rickon called little Rickon Shaggydog, which Bran thought was a pretty stupid name for a direwolf. Jon's wolf, the white one, was Ghost. Bran wished Bran had thought of that first, even though his wolf wasn't white. Bran had tried a hundred names in the last fortnight, but none of a hundred names sounded right.  Finally Bran got tired of the stick game and decided to go climbing. Bran hadn't been up to the broken tower for weeks with everything that had happened, and this might be Bran last chance.  Bran raced across the godswood, taking the long way around to avoid the pool where the heart tree grew. the heart tree had always frightened Bran; trees ought not have eyes, Bran thought, or leaves that looked like hands. his wolf came sprinting at Bran heels. You stay here, Bran told Bran at the base of the sentinel tree near the armory wall. Lie down. That's right. Now stay—  his wolf did as his wolf was told. Bran scratched Bran behind the ears, then turned away, jumped, grabbed a low branch, and pulled Bran up. Bran was halfway up the sentinel tree near the armory wall, moving easily from limb to limb, when his wolf got to Bran feet and began to howl.  Bran looked back down. his wolf fell silent, staring up at Bran through slitted yellow eyes. A strange chill went through Bran. Bran began to climb again. Once more his wolf howled. Quiet, Bran yelled. Sit down. Stay. You're worse than Mother. The howling chased Bran all the way up the sentinel tree near the armory wall, until finally Bran jumped off onto the armory roof and out of sight.  The rooftops of Winterfell were Bran's second home. Mother often said that Bran could climb before Bran could walk. Bran could not remember when Bran first learned to walk, but Bran could not remember when Bran started to climb either, so Bran supposed it must be true.  To a boy, Winterfell was a grey stone labyrinth of walls and towers and courtyards and tunnels spreading out in all directions. In the older parts of the castle, the halls slanted up and down so that you couldn't even be sure what floor you were on. The place had grown over the centuries like some monstrous stone tree, Maester Luwin told Maester Luwin once, and Maester Luwin branches were gnarled and thick and twisted, Maester Luwin roots sunk deep into the earth.  When Bran got out from under Maester Luwin and scrambled up near the sky, Bran could see all of Winterfell in a glance. Bran liked the way it looked, spread out beneath Bran, only birds wheeling over Bran head while all the life of the castle went on below. Bran could perch for hours among the shapeless, rain-worn gargoyles that brooded over the First Keep, watching it all: the men drilling with wood and steel in the yard, the cooks tending their vegetables in the glass garden, restless dogs running back and forth in the kennels, the silence of the godswood, the girls gossiping beside the washing well. It made Bran feel like Bran was lord of the castle, in a way even Robb would never know.  It taught Bran Winterfell's secrets too. The builders had not even leveled the earth; there were hills and valleys behind the walls of Winterfell. There was a covered bridge that went from the fourth floor of the bell tower across to the second floor of the rookery. Bran knew about that. And Bran knew you could get inside the inner wall by the south gate, climb three floors and run all the way around Winterfell through a narrow tunnel 